# throughput_demo.a4 — Actor message dispatch throughput benchmark
#
# PURPOSE
# =======
# Measure actual actor message dispatch performance without sleep delays.
# A single Counter actor receives N bump casts via recursive word dispatch,
# then a synchronous get_count call verifies all messages were processed.
# The sync call acts as a barrier — FIFO mailbox ordering guarantees
# all preceding casts have been handled before the call returns.
#
# WHAT IT TESTS
# =============
# - Actor creation from product type
# - Typed message dispatch (cast and call)
# - Recursive word dispatch for looping (pattern-matched base case)
# - Total throughput: N actor messages through the full dispatch pipeline
#
# N=100000 is safe for interpreted recursive words on the BEAM.
# Each iteration: construct Int literal, dispatch bump, decrement, recurse.

# Counter state — tracks number of bump messages received
type Counter
    count Int .

# bump: increment the counter (cast — no return value beyond state)
: bump Counter -> Counter ;
    count 1 + count! .

# get_count: return the current count (call — returns Int)
: get_count Counter -> Counter Int ;
    dup count .

# blast: send N bump casts to an actor via recursion
# Base case: N=0, done — just leave the Actor on the stack
: blast 0 Int Actor -> Actor ;
    swap drop .

# Recursive case: send bump, decrement N, recurse
: blast Int Actor -> Actor ;
    << bump >> swap 1 - swap blast .

# ============================================================
# Compile actor words to native BEAM for faster dispatch
# ============================================================
# The actor worker dispatches through the interpreter, which looks up
# the word in the type's operation dictionary. Compiling replaces the
# interpreted closure with a direct BEAM function call — same dispatch
# path, but the word body executes as native Erlang instead of
# token-by-token interpretation.
#
# All words including blast are compiled to native BEAM functions.
# The word compiler now supports << >> send blocks, generating
# direct gen_server:cast/call instead of interpreter dispatch.

"bump" compile
"get_count" compile
"blast" compile

# ============================================================
# Run the benchmark
# ============================================================

0 counter server

# Send 100000 bump messages via recursive dispatch
100000 swap blast

# Verify all messages arrived (sync call acts as barrier)
<< get_count >> 100000 assert-eq

# Cleanup
<< stop >> drop
